 Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Moulton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Cheshire and Lancashire): habitational name from one or more of the places called Moulton (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire, Suffolk, North Yorkshire), most of which are named with the Old English personal name <i>Mūl(a)</i>, the Old Norse personal name <i>Múli</i>, or Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Molden","meanings":["English:","metronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Mold</i>, a form of <i>Maud</i>, with the characteristically West Midland genitival suffix <i>-en</i>.","variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Moulden","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]},{"name":"Molton","meanings":["English: variant of   Moulton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":90,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William De Moulton was born about 1365, in Norfolk, England. She had at least 1 son with William De Moulton."},"et":{"about 1365–":"umbes 1365–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1385–1494":"1385–1494","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1385":"1385","1494":"1494","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Moulton, Norfolk, England":"Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1365–":"noin 1365–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1385–1494":"1385–1494","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","1385":"1385","1494":"1494","about 1365":"noin 1365","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Nor